*)Understand: During execution it will call the variables and print the message


2) Task level Variables:
------------------------

*)Variables defined inside a specific task are accessible only for that task.

*)Use Case: When variables are required only for one task.

Example:
--------

- name: task level variables
  hosts: local
  connection: local # Ansible is connecting to localhost

  tasks:
  - name: print Husband and wife names
  
    # Below vars section is task level variables, task variables are limited to only a specific task so   one task varibles cannot be used by other tasks 
    vars:
      NAME: Bujji Megham
      HUSBAND: Aaranya

    ansible.builtin.debug:
      msg: " wife is: {{ NAME }}, and her Husband is: {{ HUSBAND }}"
  
   
3) vars_files:
---------------

*)Used to load variables from an external YAML file into a playbook.

*)Use Case: To keep variables separate from the playbook and improve reusability.

*)In this case, If Variables file is present in same directory then you can directly mention the file name in playbook but 
  if it is in different path then you will have to give path of the variables file under "  vars_files: " section

Example:
--------

- name: load the variables from external file
  hosts: local
  connection: local # Ansible is connecting to localhost
  
  # kept the variables in a relationship.yaml file and loading them here. " vars_files: " is used to load the variables from external files
  vars_files:
  - relationship.yaml
  
  tasks:
  - name: print the couple details
    ansible.builtin.debug:
      msg: " wife is: {{ NAME }}, and her Husband is: {{ HUSBAND }}, bond is: {{ RELATIONSHIP }}"

